snippet.textDisplay: i hate that the government has a cure for cancer but they do not want to give it out due to them wanting to decrease  the population. my uncle died last month due to brain cancer and i wasn’t that close with him but just to know someone that was all healthy go to not being able to feed himself, not being get up to go to the bathroom or do anything and sitting there watching him suffer without there being nothing we could do about it to him taking his last breath was something that didn’t seem real. he was healthy before cancer and then he started getting sicker and then he got better then his tumor came back and they even did 2 surgeries on him to get the tumor gone but it didn’t work, he always wore a beanie because he didn’t want people to see him without any hair and he got buried in his hat and glasses that he always wore. it’s crazy to me that i can go look at pictures of him when he first got diagnosed with cancer and he looked completed fine, but i can also remember what he looked like in his casket. he only had 3-6 months to live and they went by fast and it still feels like he’s alive and i just can’t see him but i know he’s gone for good and there’s nothing i can do about it. he also died at a young age.

snippet.textDisplay: I just want to give you guys the biggest hug. You guys are two very special people and your father Sean is so very proud of you. I lost my mother at the age of 9 from ovarian cancer, she had been fighting this disease for 4 years. All the emotions that you are feeling now where exactly how I felt and till this day these emotions keep coming and going. On January 28th 2012 my mother Lise passed away and this year January 28th 2020 marked 8 years of not having her around. It hit me very hard knowing that she had been gone for this long, I still fell like only yesterday we had spoken. Great people are always the ones who leave the quickest. This life lesson is one of the hardest but it is one that will make you stronger in every way. This event will make you who you are. My mothers death only really hit me two years after. I only truly realized she wasn't ever coming back two years later. You guys are lucky to have all this support and are able to help the ones around you who have passed through this. From this video I am able to see that the emotions I felt and still feel are real, normal and are fine to share with others. You guys are loved and he will always be with you through every step of the way, maybe not physically but mentally and spiritually. If you pay close attentions to you're surroundings you will be able to feel him with you. Little details are where you will be able to feel him close to you. My mothers way of coming to see me where through butterflies. Also my mother passed away at 4:37am and ever since that day I see 37's around me. I looked it up and the meaning was that a guardian angel was watching over me and was leading me to the right path. Every time I look at the time or where ever I see this number I think of her and thank her for everything she did and what she is still doing for me. Your father seems like a very special man and did lots of good things in this world and will keep on doing even better things from where he is at this very special moment. When she got the news of the doctor that she only had a couple months left to live she didn't believe theme so we left on a cruise trip. That was are last trip together even tho she wasn't feeling her best she always had a smile on her face. Couple weeks before she passed she still didn't believe it was really going to be her last couple of days. I then told her even though it was hard that she could stop fighting for me and that she could let herself go, that I was going to be ok. It was the hardest thing I ever said but I knew it was the right thing to do. The chemo, radiation wasn't working anymore and there was nothing els to do. I just didn't was to see her suffer anymore... Just a couple days ago I found this letter that my mom had written to me, 2 months before she passed about how she wanted me to keep on traveling the world like we used to to together. She loved Europe and told me that she wanted me to go again and in march I am going to Europe for her and I, I know she will be with me through out this whole trip. At the end of the letter she wrote '' Je t'aime énormément... Maman'' with means I love you extremely... mom. and I got it tattooed on my arm to have a reminder that every day no madder what happens or what I do she will always love me. Till this day my mom friends help me and remind me of memories passed with her and funny stories of what she used to do. a couple years back I had cut 12inch of my hair to donate to make someone a wig, it was the best feeling I got in a long time knowing I would help someone in need. I hope from the bottom of my heart that all these Wonderfull donations help people who really need it. You guys probably won't ever get to read this message but even if you don't just know that you're video and me just writing this helped me a lot. God bless you two xox Manon.

snippet.textDisplay: This was amazing. The raw emotion, the honesty... everything was so beautiful. Grieving is hard. Opening up this discussion, and creating a window for others (who may be going through something similar), makes this not only a crutch for others, but a timeless piece of art. The production in its entirety was so organized, and I really felt like I was along for the journey. It was personable, and I was crying like a baby for every single second. I never knew your father, but your video introduced to me, an incredible and caring human being who lived on this earth just a state away from myself and my own family. As someone who is also your age, I can’t comprehend the pain you and your family must be going through. Thank you for sharing that pain, your process, and your strength. And thank you for spreading awareness. Wishing nothing but the best for you both, your family, and everyone who has been personally impacted by your father.

snippet.textDisplay: I remember when my grandma passed away from cancer and I felt the same way you guys did, it took me a long time to accept the fact that even though I miss her she was in a better place and wasn’t hurting anymore. I’ve now gotten to the point where when I see photos of her I don’t immediately wanna ball up, instead I hold the memories I do have with her close. I’ve had four major losses in my life and each grieving process was different but slowly I’ve found a way to cope with them and find peace. The pain of that loss will never go away but the memories I hold with them makes it just bearable. Thank you for putting such a genuine message out in the world for people who are going through the same thing.
